{"timestamp": "2026-06-27T00:00:07.539528", "user": "tell me about black holes", "nova": "Black holes are astronomical objects with such strong gravity that nothing, not even light, can escape from their gravitational pull. They form when a massive star collapses at the end of its life cycle, releasing an enormous amount of energy in the process known as supernova.\n\nThe gravitational field around black holes is so powerful that it bends spacetime itself, creating the event horizon beyond which anything, including light, cannot escape. This creates a region called an \"universe inside\" with no limits to how far away things can be from each other. The immense gravity also causes time dilation close to a black hole, making time travel and travel back in time possible near it.\n\nBlack holes play significant roles in astrophysics research and are fundamental to the understanding of gravity and spacetime curvature."}
